content.text:
You're right, 3KB is plenty. A 70-byte struct plus a few frames of call overhead is nowhere near that limit. Let me reconsider what actually happened.

The garbled output was likely the **same struct codegen bug** — tc24r generating incorrect member offsets or wrong struct type resolution when accessing `tok->type`, `tok->ival`, `tok->text` through a `struct token *` pointer. Not stack overflow.

So it's probably one bug with two symptoms:

1. **Compile-time panic** when two struct types exist and you access a member name that doesn't exist on the wrong struct (`.name` resolved against `struct token`)
2. **Wrong codegen** when accessing struct members through a pointer — wrong offsets or wrong struct type used for layout, producing garbage at runtime

Both point to the struct type tracking in `tc24r-expr-struct`. The reproducer for the runtime issue would be:

```c
struct token { int type; int ival; char text[64]; };

void scan(struct token *tok) {
    tok->type = 1;
    tok->ival = 42;
    tok->text[0] = 65; /* 'A' */
    tok->text[1] = 0;
}

void show(struct token *tok) {
    print_int(tok->type);  /* expect 1 */
    print_int(tok->ival);  /* expect 42 */
    uart_puts(tok->text);  /* expect "A" */
}

void test(void) {
    struct token t;
    scan(&t);
    show(&t);
}
```

If that produces wrong values, it's the codegen, not the stack. Want me to hold the commit until you can look at it?

input.command:
cd ~/github/sw-embed/sw-cor24-tinyc && gh issue create \
  --title "Struct member resolution fails when multiple struct types are defined" \
  --body "$(cat <<'BODY'
## Bug Description

When two struct types are defined, tc24r resolves struct member accesses against the wrong type, causing either a compile-time panic or incorrect runtime codegen.

## Symptom 1: Compile-time panic (wrong struct type for member lookup)

When accessing `.name` on a `struct keyword` variable, tc24r resolves it against `struct token` (which has no `.name` member) and panics.

**Reproducer:**
```c
struct token { int type; int ival; char text[64]; };
struct keyword { char *name; int type; };
struct keyword kw_table[2];

void foo(void) {
    kw_table[0].name = "hello";  /* PANIC */
    kw_table[0].type = 1;        /* .type exists on both, might work by accident */
}
```

**Error:**
```
thread 'main' panicked at .../tc24r-expr-struct/src/member.rs:89:9:
unknown struct member 'name' in type Struct { tag: Some("token"), members: [StructMember { name: "type", ty: Int, offset: 0 }, StructMember { name: "ival", ty: Int, offset: 3 }, StructMember { name: "text", ty: Array(Char, 64), offset: 6 }], total_size: 70 }
```

## Symptom 2: Garbled runtime output (suspected wrong offsets via pointer)

When a `struct token` is allocated on the stack and accessed through a pointer in called functions, the output is garbled (wrong values read back). This may be related to the same struct type tracking issue — if the codegen uses wrong struct layout for pointer-based member access.

**Reproducer:**
```c
struct token { int type; int ival; char text[64]; };

void scan(struct token *tok) {
    tok->type = 1;
    tok->ival = 42;
    tok->text[0] = 65;
    tok->text[1] = 0;
}

void show(struct token *tok) {
    print_int(tok->type);  /* expect 1 — may be wrong */
    print_int(tok->ival);  /* expect 42 — may be wrong */
    uart_puts(tok->text);  /* expect "A" — garbled */
}

void test(void) {
    struct token t;
    scan(&t);
    show(&t);
}
```

## Root Cause (suspected)

The struct type resolution in `tc24r-expr-struct/src/member.rs` appears to track a single "current" struct type rather than resolving from the expression's actual type. When multiple struct types are defined, it loses track of which struct an expression refers to.

## Workaround

Using parallel arrays instead of a struct with named fields:
```c
char *kw_names[27];
int   kw_types[27];
```

And using global scalar variables instead of struct-on-stack for token state.

## Context

Discovered while building the PL/SW compiler (sw-cor24-plsw), step 005 (lexer implementation).
BODY
)" 2>&1
